---
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";
import Docs from "../../layouts/Docs.astro";

const install = `- name: Install trellis
  run: |
    curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -LsSf \\
      https://github.com/tylerbutler/trellis/releases/download/v0.2.0/trellis-installer.sh | sh
    # the installer adds its install dir to $GITHUB_PATH automatically`;

const matrixWorkflow = `jobs:
  plan:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    outputs:
      matrix: \${{ steps.plan.outputs.matrix }}
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          fetch-depth: 0        # --since needs history
      - id: plan
        run: echo "matrix=$(trellis ci matrix --since origin/main)" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT"

  test:
    needs: plan
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    strategy:
      matrix: \${{ fromJSON(needs.plan.outputs.matrix) }}
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - run: trellis run test \${{ matrix.name }} --target all`;

const outputsExample = `$ trellis ci outputs
projects=["lat_core","lat_mid","lat_cli"]
releasable=["lat_core","lat_cli"]
version-files=["packages/lat_core/gleam.toml","packages/lat_cli/gleam.toml"]
tags=["lat_core-v1.2.0","lat_cli-v0.4.3"]`;

const prChecks = `# on: pull_request
- run: trellis doctor
- run: trellis changelog check --base "origin/\${{ github.base_ref }}" --json`;

const releaseWorkflow = `# on push to main: batch fragments into a release PR
- run: trellis release pr`;

const publishTagWorkflow = `# on tag push '*-v*': publish the tagged package
- run: trellis publish --tag "$GITHUB_REF_NAME"
- run: trellis lockfile refresh --package "$(trellis ci tag-package "$GITHUB_REF_NAME")"`;

const publishAllWorkflow = `# on release-PR merge: publish everything, then record tags
- run: trellis publish --all-untagged
- run: trellis tag create --github-release`;
---

<Docs
  title="CI recipes — Trellis docs"
  description="Trellis is CI-native: structured JSON for GitHub Actions matrices and outputs, doctor as a PR tripwire, and workflows that shrink to a few commands."
>
  <h1>CI recipes</h1>
  <p>
    Trellis runs identically locally and in CI, and emits the exact structures
    GitHub Actions consumes — so workspace workflows shrink to thin triggers
    around a few commands. The recipes below are the shapes a Gleam workspace
    actually needs.
  </p>

  <h2>Installing trellis</h2>
  <p>
    The shell installer puts a prebuilt binary on the runner in about a second.
    Pin the version so CI doesn't move under you (see
    <a href="/docs/installation/">installation</a> for other options, including
    a <code>.tool-versions</code> pin through mise/asdf):
  </p>
  <Code lang="yaml" code={install} />

  <h2>An affected-only test matrix</h2>
  <p>
    <code>trellis ci matrix</code> emits a strategy matrix
    (<code>&#123;"include":[&#123;"name","path","version"&#125;,…]&#125;</code>).
    With <code>--since</code> it covers only the packages a PR touched,
    dependents included:
  </p>
  <Code lang="yaml" title=".github/workflows/ci.yml" code={matrixWorkflow} />

  <div class="callout">
    <p>
      Full fan-out is the default on purpose: <code>--since</code> is opt-in
      because implicit coupling between packages — the kind the path-dep graph
      can't see — shouldn't be silently untested. A repo that wants
      affected-only CI writes <code>--since origin/main</code> into its
      workflow deliberately.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Workspace facts as outputs</h2>
  <p>
    <code>trellis ci outputs</code> emits workspace facts as
    <code>key=value</code> lines, ready for <code>$GITHUB_OUTPUT</code>:
  </p>
  <Code lang="console" code={outputsExample} />

  <h2>PR gates</h2>
  <p>
    Run <code>doctor</code> on every PR — it checks every workspace invariant
    at once and exits non-zero on any error. Pair it with
    <code>changelog check</code>, whose JSON payload (including a markdown
    <code>preview</code>) feeds a sticky comment:
  </p>
  <Code lang="yaml" code={prChecks} />

  <h2>The release pipeline</h2>
  <p>
    On every push to <code>main</code>, regenerate the release PR from pending
    fragments:
  </p>
  <Code lang="yaml" title=".github/workflows/release.yml" code={releaseWorkflow} />
  <p>
    When the release PR merges, pick one of the
    <a href="/docs/publishing/">two release shapes</a>. Tags as trigger — a
    tag-push workflow publishes each package:
  </p>
  <Code lang="yaml" title=".github/workflows/publish.yml" code={publishTagWorkflow} />
  <p>
    Or publish-then-tag — one idempotent run publishes everything not yet on
    Hex, in topological order, then records what shipped:
  </p>
  <Code lang="yaml" code={publishAllWorkflow} />
  <p>
    Because <code>publish</code> checks Hex before doing anything, re-running
    either workflow after a partial failure is safe: already-published
    versions are skipped.
  </p>
</Docs>
